xxl.cursors
Class TempCursor

java.lang.Object
  |
  +--xxl.cursors.DecoratorCursor
        |
        +--xxl.cursors.TempCursor
public class TempCursor
extends DecoratorCursor

A TempCursor doubles a given input-Iterator by providing a method named cursor that returns one instance of a BufferedCursor containg all the elements that the decorated input-Iterator (TempCursor.this) returned by calls to next().
Each time the decorated input-Iterator's method next() is called the returned element is inserted in a user-defined Queue where the BufferedCursor, tempCursor, is backed on. Only the order the elements may be returned by this BufferedCursor can be user-defined, because calls to next() and peek() are delegated from the BufferedCursor to the underlying Queue that may realize a special strategy.

Note: An input-PeekIterator or input-Iterator is wrapped to a Cursor.

See Also:
Iterator, DecoratorCursor, Queue

Method Detail

cursor

public Cursor cursor()
              throws NoSuchElementException
Returns a new BufferedCursor delivering exactly the same elements as the decorated input-Iterator (TempCursor.this) returned by a call to next(), because these elements have been inserted in the user-defined Queue. Only the order the elements may be returned can be user-defined, because calls to next() and peek() are delegated from the BufferedCursor to the underlying Queue that may realize a special strategy. Note: Only the elements that have been returned by TempCursor.this.next() are contained in the Cursor returned by this method. Furthermore this method realizes a Singleton-Design-Pattern because only one instance of a BufferedCursor is returned by this method. Every further call returns only a reference pointing to this instance.
Returns:
a BufferedCursor contaning the elements returned by the decorated input-Iterator.
Throws:
NoSuchElementException - if the iteration has no more elements.

next

public Object next()
            throws NoSuchElementException
Returns the next element in the iteration.
This element will be removed from the underlying collection, if next is called.
Each element returned by this method has been inserted in the user-specified Queue. With the help of this Queue one instance of a Cursor can be generated calling the method cursor() with the intention to receive these elements again.
